[h3 id=Comments 
	" Comments
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"I wanted to a TAS of this version since we already have TASes of the 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=N|href=/1596M)
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=E|href=/925M)
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=S|href=/1502M)
	" and 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Game Boy|href=/2766M)
	" versions, as well as the 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Tengen|href=/2581M)
	" version, the 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=Game Boy Color|href=/1405M)
	" version, and the 
	(__wikiLink|displaytext=DS|href=/1398M)
	" version. I went with Tetris B-Type Vs. Com and started from there. This game is prone to desync and it's possible to work around it. This version allows use of diagonal motion, so you can drop and slide pieces at the same time.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=StageByStageComments 
	" Stage by stage comments
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=TetrisBTypeVsCom 
	" Tetris B-Type Vs. Com
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Even with the Computer set to Hard, he can still be defeated rather quickly. I set the level to 0 and the height to 5 for me and the computer. The reason I set the level to 0 is to minimize input so that my stack won't overflow before his does. Sending 4 rows of garbage is enough to overflow your opponent's stack on height 5. To send 4 rows of garbage, is by making a Tetris or 2 triples.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=OtherComments 
	" Other comments
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Setting the computer's level to 9 costs 2 frames before setup, and there's no skip 10 levels cheat like on the NES and Game Boy versions.
	$LF
	"For Round 2, I set up for a Tetris, but the I tetromino can't come soon enough without overflowing.
	$LF
]div
